(4) It is psychologically incredible that a man of Tacitus’ rank, insight, and disposition should have seriously advised his countrymen that the beat way to subdue their old enemy would be to start a beer brewery, with aview to dispenslng the German beverage free of cost, and in unlimited quantities, implying at the same time that the Germane would gladly have accepted it, as not being supplied,a1ready with quantam con- cupiscunt, asurmise flatly contradicted by ch. 22. Moreover, this grotesque and absurdly impractlcable schema constitutes the only policy which the great historian ventured to suggest in the entire treatise -a treatise which many scholare, albeit erroneously, regard aa a political pamphlet, prinrarily designed for Trajan and directed against Roman jingoes! (b) Finally the pointed phrase, haud . . . vincentur, is, quite unlike the numerous other epigrarnmatic expressions of this author, not only utterly inappropriate, because demonstrably false, but it also bears a suspicions resemblance to «lustin l. 8, 7, prins Scythae ebrtetate qaam bello vincuntur, where the sentiment is, how- ever, in perfect keeping with the context and not open to any of the objections above referred to, but Tacitus was not in the habit of borrowing epigrama or ol misapplying those of others. The entire passage is clearly a marginal note ol some ancient reader which sub sequently waa tagged on to the close ot the chapter, and it was written at a time when triumphati magis qaam victi (ch. 37, 24) had ceased to be applicable to the Germane, i.e. about the oth century an.
